  footnotes: []
english:
  title: During Illness at Pyeong-jae
  author: Heo Geum
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Long I have lain upon this worn blue felt,
    Who remembers me enough to seek this lonely place?
    This sickly frame throughout my life—who ordained it so?
    In my prime, nothing gained, I pity only myself.

    When I comply with worldly affairs, my true purpose bends,
    I admire those ancients who adapted their way with the times.
    Should fortune rise, forget not the lamp by which I once read,
    In quiet solitude, I recall those nights we shared one quilt.
  footnotes:
    - Pyeong-jae (平齋) refers to the author's study or retreat, suggesting both a physical space and a state of mind during illness.
    - The 'blue felt' (靑氈) evokes both the humble circumstances of the poet and the worn passage of time through prolonged illness.
    - The contrast between 'worldly affairs' and one's 'true purpose' (素志) reflects the tension between pragmatic survival and philosophical ideals central to Korean literati thought.
    - The final image of sharing 'one quilt' suggests communion with a fellow scholar or spiritual companion, evoking both companionship and the hardships of their shared learning.
